Q41: Maybe to help foster a community in classes because sure there's a sense of community when I go to Girls Who Code or to Women in Software Engineering but in class I don't really get that at all. Plus, I feel like the classes are made so you do poorly and then all the sudden everyone gets a curve and that bumps their grade up by 2 grade levels. It doesn't feel like they want people to actually succeed unless they spend time outside of class doing other things regarding computer science, or spend all their time to this class. I understand that these courses are supposed to be difficult but how are people supposed to be encouraged to learn when they're constantly getting Cs and being told "oh that's normal"? I'm currently in two 300 level courses and the amount of times the students are confused and collectively need so much help just for the intro assignments doesn't feel fair. I've had my CS advisors tell me that I shouldn't take more than 2 CS courses a term because it's not feasible but then everyone else is taking 3-4 just to be able to graduate on time with the program guidelines. So the community the CS program is building is just one where all our time should be dedicated just to computer science classes but how are we supposed to make time to create personal projects for our resumes. I'm not saying to make everything easier because I do understand it's a competitive field, but at BU it's definitely a program that rewards only those who live and breath the material rather than encourage people to grow and develop their understanding of the material. Therefore, my main suggestion would be figuring out how to make the CS department something that fosters community and growth over competition and stress. My apologies if I got overzealous, I merely am an advocate for the idea that if the career and job search is going to be as competitive as it is, at the very least allow college to be a time where students are able to grow and create projects in order to properly navigate that with a strong support system.

Q37:
Asked my physics professor for help since I was struggling in a class. He told me to go to office hours for the TA’s. I went and I was still struggling and didn’t do well on my first midterm. I approached him again and he told me to get a tutor, that the engineering department pays for tutors. After that, I looked for the ENG tutors. However, at the time there was no one available for my specific physics class (engineering) for tutoring. I told him this at our final meeting, where he told me that I had to go outside BU and pay for a tutor. I told him I’m low income and cannot afford it. He said that I had to “figure out how to pay” or else “I’d fail the class and I’d have to take it another semester”. 
He never offered to help me himself. In our second meeting when going over my exam he told me it was all “common sense,” “self-explanatory,” “all in the notes.” When I told him I was still struggling he was not supportive and still treated me horribly.
